    {
      "id": 347247,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "Dicarboxylic acids have two dissociation constants, one for the initial dissociation into a monoanion and one for the second dissociation into a dianion. For oxalic acid, HO<sub>2</sub>C–CO<sub>2</sub>H, the first ionization constant is p<i>K</i><sub>a1</sub> = 1.2 and the second ionization constant is p<i>K</i><sub>a2</sub> = 4.2. Why is the second carboxyl group far less acidic than the first?",
      "answers": [],
      "hints": [],
      "formats": [
        "free-response"
      ],
      "combo_choices": [],
      "collaborator_solutions": [
        {
          "images": [],
          "solution_type": "detailed",
          "content_html": "The dianion is destabilized by repulsion between charges."
        }
      ],
